Poe and Goethe are connected through their writing. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a place called Thulé. It is a dark and lonely place. Poe's poem can be read as a companion to Goethe's "The King of Thulé." In Goethe's poem, the king is alone and sad. He has lost his will to rule or live.

Poe admired the work of other writers. He respected Alfred, Lord Tennyson, a British writer. Poe would have known Goethe's work because of his respect for Tennyson. Many copies of Goethe's work were published after the original came out, so Poe would have seen it.

Under California law, can a customer hurt in a fall on applesauce in a grocery store get extra money as punishment? This is because the store manager, Martin, was told twice about the spill and did nothing for 30 minutes to clean it up. He was eating dinner.

A judge will not quickly reject Jennifer Palmer’s claim for extra money as punishment. To get this extra money, Palmer must show that Martin on purpose did something wrong that he knew would hurt someone. She must also show that his actions were very bad. Palmer can say that Martin should have known the danger of not cleaning the spill because many people slipped and fell in the store in the months before her accident. Martin knew this, but he still did nothing.

Palmer can also say that Martin’s actions were very bad because six people slipped and fell in 2009 and he did not take action to keep the store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee, Rich Wayne, told Martin about the applesauce spill. Martin said he was busy eating dinner and did not have time to deal with customer complaints. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Martin about the spill. Martin said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill and hurt her back. Before Palmer fell, five other people had slipped and fallen at D&D Markets in 2009. Palmer is suing D&D for money to pay for her injury and for extra money as punishment.

In California, a person can get extra money as punishment if the other person acted with “badness, cheating, or evil.” The law says that evil means doing something to hurt someone on purpose or doing something very bad without trying to hurt someone. Courts have said that behavior is evil when someone knows that their actions will hurt someone and they do it anyway.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at a college in Canada.  One big question in class was if Islam is a hostile religion.  I think this is a more important question now than ever.  Looking back at what happened since 9/11, I have seen how the media talked about Islam and extremists.  I don't think it was possible in 2001 for an American president with a Muslim background, like Barack Obama, to be elected.

The story of the Prophet Muhammad interests me.  I learned that his history is different from how I thought it was.  I used to think Muhammad forced people to become Muslims.  But his story says he was a victim.  He was humble and kind.  People came to him because they believed in his ideas.

There are some similarities between the teachings of Jesus and what Muhammad did.  One example is when he shared food with many people and there was enough for everyone.  I think the writers of his story wanted to show that Muhammad was a kind and honest person.  But this makes me think they are taking away from Jesus' teachings and trying to make Muhammad seem special.

I also don't like that many stories in the biography are from people who heard from others.  This makes the stories seem less real.  I think it's not good to use stories that are not direct.

What bothers me most is that the story tries to make Muhammad seem like a great and kind person.  But history shows that he did not act that way.  I wonder if Muslims know the real story about Muhammad's rise to power.

This text is about the history of Christianity. After Jesus lived, the ideas he believed in were not followed. Instead, people moved forward with new ideas. If we look at history, we see that Christianity moved away from its start. Now, today, more people are thinking about the past and wanting to go back to the original ideas. They want to know what Jesus really said and meant.

In the future, people will become more interested in the past. They will want to know what was true about Jesus and what was not. This will take a long time, but it will happen. People will try to go back to the ideas Jesus had when he was alive. This will make Christianity return to its original form. A movement will grow and people will try to remove the new ideas that were added. They will go back to what Jesus said, not what others said later.

As this happens, the church will still be strong, but the new ideas will disappear. There will be less difference between different groups of people who believe in Christianity. They will become more alike. This is not the first time this has happened. Remember when Christians were treated badly by the Roman Empire? Later, the Roman Empire became Christian. Our country used to treat African-Americans unfairly, but now they have leaders. The Christian religion will go through a big change. This change will take people back to the beginning.

A way to make this happen is to look at Jesus' words as examples, not as things that must be true. So, what happened after Jesus lived?

We can look far back in history and see that there was only one religion, Judaism. This was the start of Christianity. People believed in one God and the Jewish scriptures were important. When the Romans took control of Jerusalem, the Jewish people were not all alike. They were divided into groups like the Sadducees, Pharisees, and others.

I think the book The Jungle shows that people are often selfish and only look out for themselves. They want to make their lives better, but they do not care about others. The book shows this in many ways. 

One main way is the factory owners and managers. They want to make their factories big and powerful. They do not care about people or animals who might be hurt by their actions. The book says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky." This shows the big damage that factories are doing. The owners do not care about the pollution from the factories or the dirty water from the animal pens. 

The owners and managers also did not care about their workers. The workers were very poor and worked in bad conditions. The factory owners would do anything to make more money. The book says, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a cauldron of hatreds and jealousies." This means the owners and workers did not care about each other. The workers were forced to work very long hours, and then the owners would lay them off without giving them any money or help finding a new job. 

In the past, there were no laws to protect workers. This meant the factory owners and managers could do what they wanted. The workers lived in very bad conditions and were treated like slaves. The book says, "Here is a population on the verge of starvation. They depend on the factory owners for their lives, and the owners are just as cruel as old-time slave drivers." This means the workers were treated very badly and had no way out of their situation.

Many authors use special ways to make readers feel a certain way about important things. Some methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these methods in his book The Great Gatsby. He pairs words that do not usually fit together to create a certain feeling. He also gives meaning to a symbol, then uses it to create a certain feeling.

Fitzgerald uses colors in a special way. He gives a special meaning to white and gray, and uses them to show the reader a certain feeling. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up the meaning for white and gray. White is like a nice, important color, and gray is like an old, faded color.

Fitzgerald shows this meaning at the beginning of the book. He says people are always wearing white. For example, Daisy and Jordan are always dressed in white. Even Nick wears white clothes to Gatsby's party. But then Fitzgerald shows people who are not wearing white. He uses these colors to show that some people are more important and some are not.

Fitzgerald also uses these colors for common things. He says Nick goes down "white chasms" when he goes to work. He says the names of people at Gatsby's parties are "gray names". He uses these colors to show that some things are important and some are not.

Later, Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show that some people are not important. He says Daisy is dressed in white, and people start to think of her as just a person that Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses this method to make readers feel a certain way about Daisy.

San Diego County is a good place for growing food. The climate is mild and sunny. Many types of food grow well here, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers.

There is a strong demand for organic food in San Diego. Many people want to buy food from local farms that use natural methods. Some farms offer tours and let visitors walk on the land. This type of farm can get government help and also make money from tours and educational programs.

Organic farming is good for the environment. It helps keep the soil and water clean. This can lead to more wildlife in the area. But organic farming can be more expensive than other types of farming. It takes more work to remove weeds and pests, and to fertilize the soil without using chemicals. Organic farms are often smaller than big farms, so they do not have the same efficiency.

The chosen land is a 160-acre area next to the town of Potrero in San Diego County, California. The land has chaparral, grass, and oak trees, and is near the Cleveland National Forest. This area is home to many types of plants and animals. Some of these animals are in danger, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher.

People have lived on this land for a long time. First, it was Native Americans, then cattle ranchers and wood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of a original homestead patent, so it was probably used for grazing or wood production for many years.

I looked at a real estate website to find a property, and then I researched government programs that can help small farmers. I found an organic farm in the same area that is an example of what this land might become.

Culture is very important in any negotiation. What culture is and what it means can be tricky to understand. A culture is not the same everywhere or for everyone. People often think of a culture as a specific thing. But it is not. For example, saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are polite" is not true. Every person is different. 

To understand a culture, you must learn about its history, its attitudes and its values. You must not judge a culture as good or bad. You must accept it for what it is. This is especially important when you are dealing with a culture that is very different from your own.

If you are in a foreign country, you must respect its traditions and customs. You must be honest and show respect. If you are in a place where the culture is very different from your own, you must be extra careful. You can learn a lot about a culture by studying its history, its values and its customs. 

A company also has its own culture. This is true even in the same country. Every company is different. For example, some companies encourage people to work long hours while others give them more time off. You can see the culture of a company by looking at how its employees dress, how they communicate with each other and how they hire new people. 

Values are very important to understand. They tell you why people behave in certain ways. If people in a culture value harmony, they will not want to cause trouble. If people in a culture value winning, they will want to win at all costs. Understanding these values will help you in a negotiation. You must also try to learn about the person you are negotiating with. This will help you to make a good deal.

The Bible says, "The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This idea is found in the Christian Bible and is also a point made by Thomas Aquinas. Both writers are trying to say God exists. We can compare their ideas because they both think of God as the God of the Bible.

Let's look at St. Anselm's idea first. He says that God is like a truth inside our minds. We know God exists because we know God is true. Anselm thinks we don't need proof from outside to know God. This is called faith. We trust in God without needing proof.

Now, let's look at St. Thomas Aquinas. He says we can know God exists through reason. We can see proof that God is real. Aquinas uses five different ideas to help us understand God. These ideas are change, causation, contingency, excellence, and harmony. He thinks that if we know the parts of something, we can know the whole. He says we can know God just by looking at the world around us.

These two writers have different ideas about how to know God. Anselm thinks faith is enough, but Aquinas thinks reason is better. We will discuss this further.

A long time ago, over two thousand five hundred years, a prince was born. He would one day be called Buddha. He grew up and later rejected the world. He became very wise and his teachings formed the new religion of Buddhism. But Buddhism has changed over time. This is clear in the country of Sri Lanka, where people celebrate the annual water-cutting ceremony. This ceremony is very important, but it was not taught by Buddha. It shows that Buddhism is different today than it was when Buddha was alive. This is true for many things, from small traditions to the main ideas of the religion.

This change is caused by many things, both from inside and outside Buddhism. Inside Buddhism, some people's ideas have changed over time. Outside Buddhism, other people's ideas have also made Buddhism different. Sometimes these changes are small and sometimes they are big.

We will use some special words in this discussion. Internal means a force that comes from people who believe in Buddhism. External means a force from people who do not believe in Buddhism. A hostile force is one that hurts or wants to hurt Buddhism. A benign force is one that does not want to hurt or help Buddhism.

First, we will look at the main ideas of Buddhism. These ideas are very important. Buddhists look to three things for help: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the teachings, which include many texts. These texts are divided into three parts: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has all the teachings of the Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for Buddhist monks and nuns. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the universe. These ideas include the idea of no soul, suffering in life, and that everything is changing.

If people understand these ideas, they can stop suffering. Suffering is a cycle of life and death. This cycle is called Sansara. When people are enlightened, they will no longer suffer from desire, hatred, and delusion. Buddhists also follow rules to live a good life. Laypeople follow five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not have sex with someone you should not, and do not take too much drink. Monks and nuns follow many more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico are two countries with a long history of rivalry. This rivalry lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The biggest problem between the two countries was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. In this war, the United States defeated Mexico and took control of Texas and the American Southwest. Many other problems happened between the two countries. These problems ended just before World War I. The rivalry started because Americans and Mexicans did not agree on many things, such as religion, customs, and traditions. They also had different interests. 

This is like many other countries that have a long rivalry with a neighbor. Countries that share a border often have disagreements that lead to a rivalry. The United States and Mexico are like many other countries with a long history of rivalry. David M. Pletcher (1977) says, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). These two countries are close to the United States and have been rivals for a long time. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States. 

The two countries disagreed on religious issues. This is a problem that has happened many times in history. Sally Frahm (2001) says, “In the past, Americans were opposed to Catholicism” (p. 86). Like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico was partly about ideas and partly about what each country wanted. In this case, the ideas were about religion. The two countries did not trust each other because of the distrust between the English and Spanish. This distrust was a big problem in the early days of their relationship. 

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 problems between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these problems were about territory. The United States and Mexico had many disagreements about border raids and other problems along the border. These problems did not end until both countries used their armies to control their borders. (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). 

Schmitt (1974) says the rivalry between the two countries started to end when Mexico became dependent on the United States. The rivalry ended when the United States stopped trying to take more land from Mexico and instead wanted to help Mexico in other ways.

Fifteen years ago, I got very sick suddenly. I was a nurse at that time. I chose nursing because my childhood was not safe. People said, "You'll always get a job because people will always be sick." I wanted a safe job. My dream was to be a scientist or a journalist. But I chose nursing instead.

Now I am 46 years old and single. I have no money and I cannot work. To this day, I am still sick. I get money from the government because I am too sick to work. After 15 years, I have nothing. Every day is hard. I am not safe, I am not secure, and I do not like how I feel about myself.

But I know one thing is true. I would not have made it without my family and friends helping me. I was very weak when I got sick. When disaster strikes, people do not feel strong.

My point is that bad things will always happen. We cannot guarantee that everything will be okay. No matter how well we prepare, some things are too big for one person to handle.

I agree that we should not trust the government too much. But I think we should help each other instead of relying on the government. We should learn to ask for help and to help others.

The people who built this country did not do it alone. They helped each other. They shared what they had. The people who crossed the country in wagons did not do it alone. They worked together.

By all means, be prepared. I have a disaster kit and first aid supplies. But I also know my neighbors. That is the most important thing. Get to know the people who live near you. They can be your friends in hard times.

We want to know why living things change over time. Are there limits that stop this change from happening? Scientists still do not fully understand this. In nineteen seventeen, a scientist named D'Arcy Thompson said it is hard to describe the shapes of living things using math. However, scientists are now using math to study how shells grow in certain animals.

We are studying how the shells of a certain type of animal called Prunum change over time. We are using math and experiments to understand how these changes happen. We looked at pictures of Prunum shells and used math to create models of how the shells might look. We then compared these models to real shells.

A shell is a tube that grows over time. It turns in a circle, or spiral, as it grows. This spiral is made up of many round circles, called whorls. Whorls are connected by a line called a suture. The last whorl, or body whorl, is the largest. The tip of the spiral is called the apex, and the bottom is called the base.

We can look at shells from different angles. There are four main ways to look at a shell: from the top, from the bottom, from the side, and from the front. The most common way to look at a shell is from the side, with the front facing the viewer.

To count the whorls on a shell, we look at it from the top and find the first line that divides the shell. We then count the whorls from this line, counting a quarter of a whorl if it is not a whole one.

A shell can be thought of as a path that the animal walks through time and space as it grows its shell. We can follow this path by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the whorl. We can use math to represent this path. Once we have this math, we can change the way the shell grows.

Indonesia has problems with many babies dying before they are one year old and after they are born.  This has not gotten better in the last ten years.  Indonesia is working to meet its goals made in 2000.  But the country is not improving as fast as it should in the important areas of child and mother health.

One good thing is that now 72% of babies have a trained health worker helping them when they are born.  But this number still has problems.  Some of these workers are not doctors and cannot help if a problem happens during birth.  This means many women die during birth.  Indonesia is not doing enough in this area.

Another problem is that fewer children under five who get sick with diarrhea are getting help from a health worker.  We also do not have enough information about how well mothers are taking care of themselves after giving birth.

Few mothers in Indonesia have a surgery called a cesarean section.  This is not good.  Even in cities, only 7% of mothers have this surgery.  In small towns, it is only 2%.  This means that many women in small towns do not have easy access to healthcare.

Some people do not have healthcare services because they are too poor.  They cannot afford to pay for the help they need.  This is a big problem.

So, the big question is: how can Indonesia fix these problems?  Should the country make special programs to help one area at a time, or should it make the healthcare system better overall?  Making special programs can be good because they have clear goals and can make things happen quickly.  But making the healthcare system better can help more people and is more important in the long run.

The problem with making special programs is that they can take money and workers away from other areas of healthcare.  This can cause other problems, like making it harder for people to get the help they need.

Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights are two novels that do not follow the normal way of Victorian novels.  Victorian novels are known for being very detailed about the lives of the wealthy people of that time.

But these two novels are different. They have mystery and strange events that make the characters more interesting. This makes us understand their feelings and reasons for doing things.

In the middle of the night, Oliver heard many confusing and scary ideas in his head. It was as if he was still talking to two men who were angry with each other. He was unsure of his body and his mind. He heard the sound of guns and people shouting. He saw lights and felt a lot of noise. He was moved quickly away from the noise. He felt pain all the time.

In Oliver Twist, strange events like this help us understand Oliver's feelings. These events show what hurts Oliver and what he thinks about the world around him. Later in the book, Oliver remembers the time he was shot. He remembers it like a dream. He is still in pain and does not know what to do. The pain makes him feel scared. It makes him think that he cannot control his life.

Oliver feels sad and helpless. He does not try to control what happens to him. This shows that Oliver does not have much control over his life. He is easily hurt by the people around him. He is hurt by Fagin, the old man who owns him.

In Wuthering Heights, there is also a strange and scary time. The day was short and night was long. It was not a normal day. The night was quiet but felt very long. Some people thought that time was passing slowly.

I worked with a group that helped students after school. I helped them with their studies. I worked with a boy named Adrian. He was having trouble reading. I thought something was strange. Some words he could read easily, but others he could not. He spoke good English, but I was sure he was of Latino descent. I met his mother one day. She did not speak English. She only spoke Spanish. We used a few words in Spanish to talk. I then understood the problem. Adrian was good at reading, but he did not know the alphabet. I tried to help him. I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story for two reasons. First, it shows that language can be a big problem in schools. Second, it shows that the problem is not always easy to see. Even if a child speaks good English, reading can still be hard. We all know that this is a problem. So, what do we do? In Adrian's case, I helped him with reading. But for other children who do not speak much English, the problem is more complicated. There is no one answer. We need to use many different ways to help.

One good idea is the dual language system. This means teaching children in two languages. Not just for children who speak Spanish at home, but for all children. This system works well. Children in dual language classes do better in school. Some people are afraid of this idea. They think it is not worth the money. But it is true. All children would benefit from this system if we used it more. To make it work, we do not need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have helpers who are bilingual. This can make a big difference.

Most of us are told from a young age that there is something bigger than us. Some people go to Sunday school, others to the Temple, and some search for answers on their own. Many of us believe what our parents teach us. But some of us disagree and think there is no more to life than what we can see and touch. We may change our values many times. Each person's idea of spirituality is different.

My father said cardinals are his favorite birds. We sat on our front porch and listened to the rain. Rain poured down from the gutters and drowned the plants. My father looked out at the rain, thinking or remembering something. He was thinner and looked tired. His hair was thinning too. I was afraid and sad because my father was going to die. I didn't want to talk about it because it would make it more real. I hugged him and sat close to him.

My father died in December, five days after my birthday. He was in pain, but treatment kept him alive a few more months. I didn't understand why he had to suffer so long. I thought to myself, what kind of God would do this? I didn't say any prayers that night. If God existed, I thought, he wasn't listening to me.

I didn't want to watch my father die. I chose to remember him the way he lived, not how he died. My father would have wanted me to be happy, not sad. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for the news. But no one called me.

The term "Gothic Novel" is a combination of old and new ideas. Ian Watt describes it as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New.'" Many people have different opinions about Gothic novels. Some think they are not very deep, while others think they are great. The first Gothic novel was written by Horace Walpole in 1764. It is called "The Castle of Otranto." Walpole used old ideas and new ways of writing to create a new kind of story.

Walpole's "Gothic Story" combines old and new elements. He used old theatrical ideas and new ways of writing to create a new kind of story. The Gothic genre also uses old ideas about medieval times, such as gothic architecture and traditions.

When "The Castle of Otranto" was first published, the word "gothic" was used to describe many different things. Some people thought it was old-fashioned and not very sophisticated. The combination of old and new ideas makes Gothic novels remain popular for a long time.

One idea that is important in Gothic novels is the concept of chivalry. Chivalry is a medieval idea about how to be a good knight. In "The Castle of Otranto," the idea of chivalry is used to show what is good and what is not. The writers of Gothic novels, like Walpole, thought that society was not living up to the ideals of chivalry.

The character Frederic in "The Castle of Otranto" is a good example of chivalric ideas. He is a prince who has suffered a lot and is very polite and kind. He is an example of the "gallant and courteous Knight" that is often used in Gothic stories.

The Gothic genre is complex and has many different ideas. It uses old and new elements to create a new kind of story. Gothic novels often use chivalric ideas to show what is good and what is not. They often use old ideas about medieval times to create a new kind of story.

Supply chain management is a system of processes. These processes take goods from the customer's order to the raw materials stage, then to the supply, production, and distribution of products to the customer. The term supply chain management was first used in 1982 by a man named Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver explained how to plan, do, and control these processes to please customers quickly and efficiently.

There are six important parts to supply chain management: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process. It is the base for all the other steps. Production decides when, why, where, and how products will be made. To do this, managers must know what customers want. To find out what customers want, managers look at the market. The market is the biggest sign of what customers need. Once managers understand customer needs, they decide what products to make and how many to make. They also decide where to make the products and which factory will make them best. This helps meet customer demand and make customers happy.

The next step is for managers to plan work and take care of equipment. Production is very important. If anything goes wrong, it can cost the company time and money.

Supply is the second important part of supply chain management. Supply means making strategic decisions about what a company can do well and who to partner with. A company may have many teams working on a single product. Each team has its own equipment, workers, and special skills. The manager decides which team is best for each task. The manager may also decide to work with another company to help make the product. This is called outsourcing. The goal is to be fast and flexible while saving money.

The story is about a movie star named Patricia Neal. She was a beautiful and successful actress. She was born in Kentucky in nineteen twenty-six. Her father worked in a coal mine. The town where she was born no longer exists. But Patricia Neal is remembered for her beauty, success, and bravery.

When Patricia Neal was a teenager, she started acting. She studied at a university in Illinois and then moved to New York City. In nineteen forty-seven, she won a special award for her first time on Broadway. This made her popular quickly. She was soon offered roles in Hollywood movies.

Patricia Neal was on the cover of a famous magazine when she was just twenty-one. This meant she was a big star. Millions of people read the magazine every week.

In Hollywood, Patricia Neal met a famous actor named Gary Cooper. They worked together in a movie called “The Fountainhead” in nineteen forty-nine. They fell in love, but their love was short. Patricia Neal had a child with Gary Cooper, but he did not want to leave his wife for her.

After that, Patricia Neal met a writer named Roald Dahl. They married in nineteen fifty-three. They had five children. Patricia Neal acted again on Broadway and in movies. In nineteen sixty-four, she won an Oscar for her best performance. She was very happy.

But Patricia Neal suffered two big problems. A car hit her young son, and he was hurt badly. Her seven-year-old daughter died from a sickness. Patricia Neal was very sad.

In nineteen sixty-four, Patricia Neal had a bad accident. She had three strokes. She was in a coma for three weeks. When she woke up, she could not see or speak. It was hard for her to move her body. People thought she was dead, but she was not.

Patricia Neal worked hard to get better. Her husband helped her. She was not able to walk or speak for a long time. She said she hated her life, but she did not give up. She had a healthy baby girl six months later.

Patricia Neal went back to acting in nineteen sixty-eight. She worked hard, but it was hard for her to remember her lines. She was nominated for an Oscar again. She played a mother who was angry and hurt.

In nineteen seventy-eight, Patricia Neal opened a special center to help people who had strokes. She wanted to help others who were like her. She said, “Stubbornness gets you through the bad times. Don’t give in.”

Patricia Neal was married for thirty years to a man who had a long relationship with her friend. She was very sad. She left him and moved back to the United States. Patricia Neal was eighty-four when she died of cancer in two thousand ten. She made many movies and TV programs. She was a brave and successful actress.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz music is very important. He lived a long time and was able to write many great songs. Ellington is not always on the piano in his compositions, but he was great at writing music that showed off the talents of each band member. He created a framework for soloists to improvise, and also wrote music with a clear style that fit each piece. This made his orchestra sound unique.

Ellington understood the sound of each player and how they worked together. He used this understanding to write some of the most innovative jazz music ever. He also used voice as a musical instrument in his music. This was something new and exciting at the time.

A good example of this is his song “Creole Love Call.” In this song, Ellington uses voice in a way that adds texture and color to the music. It is a slow, twelve-bar blues song with six parts. Each part is different, and shows off the skills of the different band members.

Part one is a call and response between voice and reeds. The voice begins smooth, but gets rougher at the end. Part two has a muted trumpet solo that emphasizes some sad notes. Part three has a clarinet solo that is high and exciting. Part four has the whole band playing together, with a call and response between the brass and reed sections. Part five is the most exciting part, with the reeds making the call and the brass and rhythm sections playing in a special way. Part six is like the first part, but the voice sounds like an instrument.

Ellington used voice to add color to his music in many of his songs. This was a new and interesting way to write music. He was a master of making his band sound great.

In another song, “Hot and Bothered,” Ellington uses his skill at writing tight music to make a call and response between the trumpet and voice sound rich and full. He also uses the trombone to create a new sound.

Ellington’s music is full of new and interesting ideas. He was a true master of jazz.

She never felt complete. This feeling started when she was 14 years old. It was still there when she was 17. She knew she wanted a person, not just a thing. But she was not interested in boys. Some boys liked her, but she did not feel the same way. She wondered why this was happening. She had thought about it for many years, but could not find the answer.

Her home was usually a peaceful place. Her parents were calm people who did not argue. They rarely argued with her, too. They just wanted her to be happy. But they worried about her independent spirit. She was a happy person with a fun personality.

Today was not a peaceful day. She was looking for something to do when she heard a loud cry from the kitchen. She ran in and saw her mother on the floor in pain. Her mother was saying "Ow" over and over. The daughter ran to help. "Mom, what's wrong?" she asked. Her mother said, "Ouch, sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital." The daughter helped her mother up and carried her to the car. They went to the hospital.

The hospital was a scary place. It smelled like sickness and medicine. But she was too worried about her mother to feel scared. She called for help and some doctors came. They put her mother on a bed and took her to see a doctor. The daughter was very worried.

Her mother had fallen off a stool trying to get a vase from a high cabinet.

This study was to see if eating a diet like the people eat in the Mediterranean area can help lower the risk of heart disease and stroke.  The researchers looked at a diet called the aMed diet. It is a special diet that includes lots of plant foods, like fruits, nuts, and whole grains. It also includes fish and less animal products and saturated fats.

Past studies showed that people who eat the Mediterranean diet have lower risk of death from heart disease. But these studies did not look at stroke. So, this study wanted to find out if the aMed diet can help lower the risk of stroke.

The study followed 74,886 women between the ages of 38 and 63 for 20 years. The women were all nurses who were part of a bigger study of 121,700 nurses in 11 states. The researchers asked the women about what they ate six times between 1984 and 2004. They used a special form to ask about their food habits. Almost all the women kept participating in the study for 20 years.

The researchers found out about heart disease and stroke cases by looking at medical records and reports. They also looked at other factors that could affect the results, like smoking, body weight, and exercise. To get a better idea of the women's eating habits, they averaged the scores from the food forms over two years.

The results showed that women who ate more like people in the Mediterranean area had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. Women who ate the most like this had a 29% lower risk of heart disease and stroke compared to those who ate the least like this.

In 2007, the United States had a big economic problem. Many people lost their jobs, the housing market crashed, and some big companies were in trouble. We ask: how did this happen and how can we stop it from happening again? In simple words, the economic problem was caused by people in power making selfish and foolish decisions. They forced banks to give out bad loans to people who could not pay them back. The banks then sold these bad loans to other companies, and when people could not pay, the banks were in trouble.

The roots of the problem started in 1999. The President at that time wanted to be re-elected. He wanted to be popular so he changed the rules to make it easier for people to get loans. This made it easy for banks to give out bad loans. In 1999, a writer for the New York Times wrote: “Fannie Mae, a company that helps people buy homes, was under pressure to give out more loans to people with little money. This could cause problems when the economy gets bad.” He said this would lead to a big problem that would need help from the government.

Many things happened that made the economy get worse. Banks gave out new kinds of loans that were hard to understand. These loans were called adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs). These loans connected many parts of the economy to the housing market. This made people and banks very dependent on the housing market. When the housing market crashed, they were in big trouble.

The five biggest banks in the United States had $4.1 trillion dollars of bad loans in 2007. This was 30% of the country's total money. In the end, some banks went out of business and others became smaller and had to follow strict rules. Fannie and Freddie, two big companies that helped people buy homes, had $5 trillion dollars of bad loans and were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition is a part of writing that can be tricky. It's when you tell your readers a lot of information all at once, usually to explain something that happened before the story starts. This can be boring and make your readers lose interest.

Many writers know the rule "Show, don't tell." But even experienced writers can still get stuck in long parts of the story where nothing happens. This is called exposition. It's like a voice in your head that says, "Let's get the history out of the way so we can get to the good parts."

Exposition is like a character telling another character a long story. It's when an author tells the reader what happened before the story starts.

Imagine reading a story. You are told that the main character met her husband, got married, and he was murdered. You wouldn't expect that to take two pages. You would want to see how the husband loved his wife and how she loved him. You would want to understand why his death was so important.

As a writer, you need to add "meat" to the story. You need to show the reader how the characters feel and what they think. You can't just tell them. You need to make them care about what's happening.

It's easy to rush past some parts of the story. But that's where the best writing happens. Take the time to show your readers what's going on. Don't just tell them. Give them something to think about and feel.

I watched two news programs from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was on NBC 4 this morning. The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio. He stabbed his wife. The police arrested him. His name is Shad Hostettler. The news did not show her picture. They only spent two minutes on the story because it is still happening.

The next story was about a shooting in the Sharon Woods area. An 18-year-old man was shot. He is in the hospital. Nobody has been arrested yet. The police are investigating.

I think the news did not give enough time to this story. If a white person had been shot, the news would have spent more time on it. But because the man is black, the news did not spend much time on it.

The next story was about a helicopter that was shot by a bullet. It was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. The police want help to find the person who did it. They are offering a five-thousand-dollar reward.

The news also said there will be rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. The temperature will be in the middle to low eighties. They only talked about this for a short time. They wanted to keep us watching.

The news also talked about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A man robbed the store. He is black. He was wearing a hooded sweatshirt. He is 6 feet tall and weighs 150 pounds. I think they talked about his color too much.

Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a big drug dealer in Texas. He was sent to prison for 300 months. That is 25 years. He is Hispanic. I do not think his color is important for this story.

There is a strong connection between brothers. This connection is hard to break and is very special. Inside this connection are many feelings: love, pride, anger, and hurt feelings. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. They can see themselves when they look at their brother. In bad times, the true nature of this connection is shown. When brothers feel strong emotions, they often pay a price. Part of understanding these emotions is dealing with the results of those emotions. When you look at your brother, you see a part of yourself. You see how others see you, but also how you really are. Your actions and the results of those actions show your true character.

The story of "The Scarlet Ibis" shows this connection between brothers. The two boys are very different. One is healthy and strong. The other is sick and weak. They go on a journey together. Disappointment and pride are strong feelings that come out in the end. Only one brother survives. The story shows how the strong brother feels about his little brother. He wanted a brother to play with and to teach things to. But the little brother was sick and could not do the things the strong brother wanted. The strong brother felt angry and sad. He even thought about hurting the little brother. But when the little brother smiled, the strong brother felt happy and loved him. This shows that the strong brother really loved his brother.

The story says that brothers understand each other very well. They can see themselves in each other. What brothers feel and do shows who they really are. In the story, the strong brother feels many strong feelings. He feels angry and sad, but he also feels happy and loving. The story teaches us about the connection between brothers.

The human brain is a very complex system. It helps us think and make decisions. As time passed and technology improved, people used new words to describe the brain. At first, it was like a piece of paper, then a book, and now it is like a computer. These comparisons are not very useful and can lead to mistakes.

The brain gets information from our senses. It changes these feelings into electrical signals. The brain uses these signals many times. It uses two ways of processing: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up means the brain puts simple information together. Top-down means the brain uses what it already knows to make things easier.

Let's say you see a picture of a black box. Bottom-up helps you see the box's color, shape, and edges. Top-down helps you recognize it as a box. You might also think it's a black box on a white background.

The brain decides what is important and what to do with the information. This is called the attention filter. You can think about many things at the same time, but the filter helps you focus on what's important. For example, you might hear your name in a noisy room.

The brain stores information. This includes three types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. The information is encoded first. It is like a code. There are different codes for different types of information. For example, when you hear words, the brain uses the words' sounds, shapes, and meanings.

The brain keeps information by using electrical signals. This signal goes between certain brain cells for a short time. Long-term memory is thought to be kept in special proteins in the brain.

Scientists have many ideas about how the brain organizes information. Some ideas come from how people remember things, some come from computer science, and some come from studying the brain. The semantic network idea says that the brain has nodes, or points, that are connected. These points are linked because they are related. For example, the word "chair" might be connected to the word "table," which might be connected to the word "wooden."

Aldous Huxley writes about the dangers of technology and capitalism in his novel Brave New World. He uses a story to show what could happen if people value community above the individual. The people in the story are told what is good for them, and they are not allowed to think for themselves.

The people in Brave New World are conditioned to be happy and not to question the government. They are told to obey the World Controller. This is not a real democracy, but a system where one person is in charge.

Huxley criticizes capitalism by showing how people are controlled. They are not allowed to think about their relationships with others in the community. They are only interested in making money and being happy. The people at the bottom of the social ladder, called Deltas, Gammas, and others, are not free to make their own choices. They are told what to want and how to want it. This is called false consciousness.

The people at the top of the social ladder, called Alphas and Betas, know about the system, but they do not do anything to change it. They are comfortable with their place in society.

Huxley also shows that people in Brave New World do not have deep relationships. They do not really know each other. They talk about each other's bodies, not about their feelings. This is not a real way to live. It is a way to keep people from thinking for themselves.

The people in Brave New World are happy to do what they are told. They do not want to be different or to question the government. This is a criticism of capitalism and how it controls people.

Huxley is saying that technology and capitalism can take away people's freedom and ability to think for themselves. He is warning us about what could happen if we do not be careful.

I am a student at University Park. I have been here for about two and a half years. Getting around campus can be hard. My freshman year, I lived in an East Halls dorm room, which is far from the rest of the school. It takes a long time to walk from my home to classes in other parts of campus. I have to walk from Stuart Hall to the Willard building, which can take up to 25 minutes. Sometimes it's hard to walk in bad weather.

I learned that a long time ago, the East Halls dorms were not connected to the rest of the school. There was empty land between them. Now, the empty space has buildings and sports fields.

As the campus grows, it's harder to move around. The best solution is to ride a bike. But a bike by itself is not enough. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be easy for cyclists.

I talked to a friend who rides a bike again after a long time. He said, "Bikes are great. It's the best way to get around." Riding a bike is good exercise and very efficient. You can ride 30 miles or more after eating a simple breakfast.

I live off campus, which is far from the center of campus. I bought a bike and it's the smartest thing I've done this year. It takes 5 minutes to ride to Thomas building, which is where I have class. If I don't have my bike, I have to walk, which would take 30-40 minutes. That's a lot of extra time.

If I have to walk a lot, it will take over two and a half hours every week. That's too much time for me. I'm too busy. A bike helps me save time and be more efficient.

original_texts:
In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life.
