She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to help people in need. I want to work with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who are being hurt or neglected. I also want to help families who are having problems.

The values I will bring to this job are important. They include helping others, treating people with respect, being honest, and working hard to improve myself so I can help people better. These values are important to me, not just for my job, but also for my life.

I have always wanted to help others. But I was not sure what job I wanted. In high school and college, I saw many people avoid their problems and some made bad choices. This made me think about a career in Psychology. But I was still not sure. So I took a break after I finished college in 2009.

One day that summer, I visited a friend. She had a 16-year-old boy visiting her. He was very nervous. She told me why he was there - to escape his mean parents. The next day, I went to the parents' house to see if I could help. I talked to the police and explained that I was a psychologist. They asked me to talk to the parents. When I asked them about the boy, they seemed nervous and made excuses. This made me think about how I could help children like this boy.

I also care about social justice. We say that each person is important, but we often want to be like everyone else. I am different and I do not want to be limited by what others think. In high school and college, I stood up for what I believed in. I wore clothes that were my style, I had bright hair colors, and I spoke out against racism and unfairness. I will continue to stand up for what I believe in.

This paper looks at two ways to understand a sleep problem called insomnia. The first way is called the biological model. This model looks at things like genes and medical problems that can affect sleep. The second way is called the sociocultural model. This model looks at how sleep is affected by things like race, income, and where people live.

The biological model studies how genes and medical problems can affect sleep. For example, a study with mice found that special molecules called orexin help regulate sleep and wakefulness. The study showed that a certain kind of receptor in the brain called GABAB can affect sleep. The researchers found that a special medicine called baclofen can help mice sleep. This means that the research on mice can help us understand how sleep works in humans.

The sociocultural model looks at how sleep is affected by things like where people live and how much money they have. If people inherit a problem with their GABAB receptors, it can affect their sleep. This can make it hard to do everyday tasks like going to school or work.

Insomnia is a sleep problem that can be caused by different things. It can be a primary sleep disorder, which means it is a sleep problem on its own. Or it can be caused by another mental health problem. Insomnia can also be caused by medical problems or taking certain substances.

There are different types of sleep disorders, including insomnia, hypersomnia, narcolepsy, and others. Insomnia is when a person has trouble sleeping, and hypersomnia is when a person has trouble staying awake. Narcolepsy is a sleep disorder that involves falling asleep suddenly.

The sociocultural model looks at how things like race, income, and where people live can affect sleep. For example, some people may have trouble sleeping because of stress or because they do not have a comfortable place to sleep.

This paper will look at the biological and sociocultural models of insomnia and discuss the strengths and weaknesses of the research.

This paper talks about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, we will explain what the disorder is. Next, we will discuss how to diagnose it. Finally, we will talk about how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD is a problem with how the brain uses what we hear. The brain cannot process sound correctly. People with CAPD can hear normally, but have trouble with things like understanding what is said in a noisy room. They can hear, but their brain does not work correctly to help them understand.

The first time people talked about CAPD was in the 1950s. They called it “auditory imperception.” Researchers started testing children with communication problems back then. In 1954, an Italian team developed tests for children with these problems. In 1961, a scientist named Kimura created a way to test how the brain works when we hear two things at the same time.

CAPD makes it hard for people to do several things. They may have trouble knowing where a sound is coming from. They may have trouble hearing two or more sounds. They may not be able to recognize patterns in sound. They may not be able to tell when someone is being sarcastic. One sound can block out another sound. They may not be able to understand how to use sounds to do things. And they may not be able to tell when sounds are in the right order.

To diagnose CAPD, a person must be tested. This can be done by a specialist who listens to what the person does and how they respond to different sounds. There is no single test that can diagnose CAPD. Many tests ask the person to do things like listen to a series of words or numbers. Some tests also record the sounds in the ear and see how the person responds.

The play Twelfth Night says that disguises can be useful, but they can also cause problems. If a person hides their true identity for too long, they may lose themselves. Ending a deception can also be difficult. It may cause people to be angry or sad. They may feel hurt because they were tricked.

Disguises can also cause problems in relationships. For example, in Twelfth Night, a woman named Viola pretends to be a man to protect herself. She is very good at pretending, but it makes her feel alone. She is not close to the women around her. This causes her more problems.

Viola's disguise also causes confusion. People think she is a man named Sebastian. Another woman, Olivia, falls in love with the wrong person. This is a big problem.

The play also shows how disguises can help people hide their true feelings. For example, Olivia and Orsino, two main characters, seem to have hidden feelings for each other. But they do not act on these feelings because Viola is pretending to be a man. When Viola's disguise is discovered, it makes Olivia and Orsino face their hidden feelings.

Some people think that Olivia's feelings for Viola were not real. They think she was just attracted to Viola because she thought she was a man. But Olivia's behavior is also suspicious. She quickly stops loving Viola and starts to love the "real" Sebastian. This shows that Olivia may be making fun of people who judge others based on how they look.

The play is saying that disguises can be complicated and cause problems. People must decide between being true to themselves and keeping their relationships. It is not always easy.

German colonial rule was very bad. The Germans were very cruel to the Ovaherero and Nama people in South West Africa. This is just one example. The German colonial empire was different in many ways. It had different rules and leaders in different places. The education system was also different in different colonies. When the British took control of Tanganyika (East Africa) in 1919, they found many Africans who could read and write. Germans did good work in Kamerun and other colonies, according to writers at that time.

But in South West Africa, the situation was very bad. In East Africa, the government built schools and helped teach Africans. In South West Africa, the government did not help very much. Missionary groups taught many Africans, but they did not have much money or help from the government. The government spent a lot of money on schools for Europeans in the colony. They made sure Europeans had good education. These education policies lasted a long time in South West Africa. Other German colonies had many Africans who could read and write. But in South West Africa, most people were not educated.

There are many books and articles about education in the German colonial empire. Many of these are in German and were written a long time ago. These books mainly described the education systems in the colonies. Later, writers in English wrote more about education in the German colonies. They compared education in different colonies and looked at specific parts of the education system. One important book is by Cohen, who studied education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen says the number of white settlers in South West Africa made the education system in this colony different.

South West Africa has a mild climate, but it is also a desert. Many Europeans lived there because it was a good place to live. In 1913, over 15,000 Europeans lived in South West Africa. Only 5,336 lived in East Africa, which had the next largest number of European settlers.

Many kinds of music are part of the Popular Music group. This group has changed a lot in the last 100 years. New kinds of music are being added every year. Most kinds of music have broken down into smaller groups. For example, rock music has many smaller groups like heavy metal.

Heavy metal music is one of the most interesting kinds of music. It shows many different feelings, but usually it is dark and sad. People who make heavy metal music started to make their own kinds of music. This started a chain of new kinds of music. Now there are many kinds of heavy metal.

It is hard to say what heavy metal is. Many kinds of music have joined it. But it started from something. To understand heavy metal music, you must know where it came from.

Heavy metal is a kind of music that is dark. It is loud and has a lot of beat. People who make heavy metal music are very good at their instruments. They show this in their music. Heavy metal music is also often about complicated feelings and is influenced by drugs. Many people used psychedelic drugs in the 1970s. This led to new and strange music. Heavy metal music has many dark qualities. It shows feelings that most music does not show.

Heavy metal has taken some of its ideas from the Romantic Era. This era was very emotional and sad. Many heavy metal songs are about these strong feelings. For example, the song "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles is a famous heavy metal song. It shows the darker side of the Beatles. This song was a response to another song by the Rolling Stones. The Beatles wanted to show they could make heavy music too.

Henri Rousseau painted his dream. But his dream was not just in the painting. It was also his own dream as an artist. The Dream, a painting from nineteen ten, shows a woman looking at the wonders of a magical place in her dream. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and goals. He wanted to be recognized and admired by other artists and people who love art. But he had a big problem. He had to choose between being like other artists and being himself.

To understand Rousseau's painting, we need to know something about his life. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, eighteen forty-four, in a small town in northwest France. His father was a businessman. Rousseau grew up without any formal training in art. He worked for many years until he was forty. He was an employee of the government, collecting taxes at the border. People sometimes called him a customs inspector.

Rousseau's first wife died when their eight babies were young. He was left with one daughter, Julia, and a lot of sadness. He wanted a new life. He started painting to find comfort. Rousseau was not like other artists who painted beautiful pictures of peasants. He was a folk painter. He painted about common people like himself.

Rousseau wanted to be accepted by the art world. He was not educated in art, and he started painting late in life. Many other artists were famous and well-known during that time. Rousseau did not get recognition until Matisse became famous. A writer said that Rousseau and Matisse were different. Matisse wanted to paint in a special way to avoid being boring. Rousseau wanted to paint in a way that would make people accept him as a good artist.

The Dream is Rousseau's work that shows his big problem. He wanted to fit in and be accepted, or be himself and be different. This was a problem he had his whole life.

Many people think there is a strong connection between what is right and wrong (ethics) and what is beautiful (aesthetics). I think there is a good reason for this. A famous writer, John Keats, once said, "Beauty is truth. Truth is beauty. That is all / You know on earth, and all you need to know." We learn many things in life, but we often know when something is beautiful or right without being taught. We try to explain why something is beautiful or right, but we can't always give a complete answer. Our studies of morality and beauty are not just about rules, but about understanding why something is good or beautiful. 

When people talk about why a painting or a book is good, they often use words like "good" or "beautiful," but it's hard to describe exactly what makes it so. For example, when someone talks about the famous painting "Mona Lisa," they might talk about the background or the face, but it's hard to explain why it is so special. When asked why they like a certain book or picture, people often say, "There's just something about it." I think that's true for both art and morality. Even if we try to explain the good qualities of a piece of art or a moral idea, there is something more to it that we can't fully explain. This "something" is what I think makes art and morality special.

I think art and morality are connected because they both touch us deeply, even if we can't fully understand them. They are hard to explain, but we know when we experience them. This connection is especially strong when we talk about literature. Literature is a special kind of art that deals with values and what is right and wrong. We find meaning and values in literature that we can apply to our lives.

The Germany of today is a strong country with a special culture. It is a mix of different parts and influences. You can feel this mix in many cities, like München near the Alps and Kiel near the Baltic Sea. The same feeling is in cities like Köln on the Rhine River and Dresden on the Elbe River.

Germany has a long history. Many different groups and tribes have lived there. The country we know today comes from these different groups.

Germania is the land where the Germans come from. But where did the name "Germania" come from? Some people think it comes from a group called the Tungrians, who were also called Germans. They lived near the Rhine River. They fought with a group called the Gauls.

The Roman leader Julius Caesar used the word "Germanus" to talk about the Germanic tribes. He got this word from the Gauls. Caesar used it to talk about the tribes he had not conquered. He wrote about the Germans in his book about the Gallic Wars. He said they lived beyond the Rhine River and fought with the Gauls all the time.

Other people think the name "Germania" comes from a spear called a "ger." Or it might come from an old Irish word that means "to shout." This means the Germans were loud.

A Roman historian named Tacitus wrote a book about the origins of the Germans. He said they were the original people of the area. They did not come from other places and mix with other groups. They were a separate people.

The Romans did not live in Germany. They would go to Germany to trade and fight, but they did not stay. The Germanic tribes lived near the Roman Empire and traded with them. They also served in the Roman army.

I stared down at the view in front of me. My mind was empty and blank. I looked at the picture without thinking about it. My thoughts came and went quickly. It was like my mind was watching something, but not really thinking about it. 

I used to want to learn how to draw. When I was a little boy, six years old, I wanted to draw. I got a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." It teaches people how to draw. It says to put a square around a picture to make it simpler. This helps people see what is important. 

I was looking at a bowl of fruit on a table. I had trouble thinking about the table as a simple plane. I was too busy looking at all the details. I felt like I was seeing something amazing. 

Many artists, like Picasso and Monet, used different colors in their work. I wanted to be a good artist. I wanted to make something special. I named my picture "Work in Brown." 

My hand was moving to draw, but then it stopped. I was using the toilet. I was trying to get rid of something. It was brown and not pretty. I wanted to get rid of it. I had a mop in my hand. I was standing with my feet apart, wearing a green tie. I was not happy about the mess. 

I tried to clean it, but it would not go down the toilet. I got frustrated. I thought about how I must be the only one to clean the bathroom at Rite Aid. I got some toilet paper and put my hand in it. I was trying to get my hand clean. 

I used toilet paper to make my hand clean. It was hard to do. I had to bend down and use my hand to take out the dirty thing. It was a sad and dirty job. I was not happy about it.

Many young people are killed in car accidents.  There are several reasons for this problem.  The National Institutes of Health say that one reason is that the teen brain is not ready for the dangers of driving.  Young drivers also have little experience behind the wheel.  This causes more accidents and more bad driving.  Teens do worse when they drive with their friends.  A study in California showed that older passengers are safer.

California and other states try to make driving safer for teens by limiting the hours they can drive and who they can take with them.  But some think these rules are not enough.  The problem is that teens are not ready to handle the risks of driving.  A psychologist says 18 is too young to get a driver's license.  He says young people often want to take risks for fun.  It makes sense to wait until this wanting to take risks goes away.

If we give driver's licenses to young teens, we will see more accidents.  The number of people killed in car accidents will be very high.  In a few years, a lot of new drivers will be on the road.  We can make a law to solve this problem.  Schools can teach people how to drive, but no one under 18 can drive a car.  A learner's permit can still be given before a full license.  People must practice driving with an adult for a certain number of hours.  The number of hours can be the same as most states now use.  This law would help stop teen drivers from getting hurt.

This idea is not new.  We just need to make it a national law so it helps everyone.

I looked at films from the Library of Congress's collection of old Edison films. I wanted to watch all the trick films made from 1895 to 1901. There were 15 of them. These films make use of special editing to create tricks. My study focused on how these films use words and examining some special features of a few later films.

Most trick films from that time are set in one place. They do not use camera movement. They use long and medium shots. They follow a rule that one shot of film equals one scene. However, some early films break these rules by using more than one shot.

A common feature of trick films is that they are filmed inside a set with a front stage. The camera does not move from this position to follow actors or objects. This style comes from the theatre and magic shows. Because of this style, actors do not move towards or away from the camera. They only move from side to side.

For example, in the film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth along the stage. The camera does not move with them.

Most trick films are long shots and, less often, medium shots. Close-up shots are not used in any of the trick films from the Edison collection. This is because the theatre and magic shows do not use close-up shots. The audience sees the whole performance at one time, framed by the stage borders.

Most trick films are short, lasting about one minute or less. They often show short magic tricks, such as disappearing and switching acts with little story. However, a single shot in a trick film can be made up of several joined shots to create an illusion. For example, in the film "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), a closer look shows the moment when the shot with Mary's "severed head" begins, even though the whole film is one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was a strong supporter of Republicanism.  He was a farmer, but his work in politics made him famous for his ideas about freedom and government.  He believed that farming was the best way to live.  This idea helped shape his ideas about the government and its power.  He wanted to protect and help farmers like himself.

John Taylor thought the United States was lucky.  It did not have old traditions that could block the creation of a good government.  He believed people have natural rights that are very important.  These rights include freedom and the right to own property.  He thought these rights should be safe from the government.  He said that in a natural state, people with strength and bad intentions often win.  But in a civilized society, this should not be true.

To make a perfect society, Taylor thought the government should help people be good and not evil.  He believed that the government should be fair and just.  He said governments are like people – they can be good or bad.  He believed that good principles are those that protect property, help farming, and are fair to all people.  A good government would work well no matter who is in charge.  He thought people are motivated by self-interest, but this is not always bad.  It is bad when it hurts others.

John Taylor wanted the government to follow the rules of the Constitution closely.  He wanted a small government with only the powers listed in the Constitution.  He thought a big government is expensive and can be unfair.  But he also thought that following the rules too strictly can be a problem.  He believed that the Declaration of Independence is more important than the Constitution.  It says the United States is a group of states, not just one country.

There was a big drop in the number of people filling out the commuter log in the third month of the project. This was a problem. It was hard to know why this happened. The winter season had started at the college. Fewer people ride bicycles or walk to school. This could be one reason for the drop. It was also the end of the fall semester. People were busy with schoolwork and finishing their grades. They may not have had time to fill out the log. The holiday season started in December. Students and teachers do not have to come to school. This means there were fewer people who needed to use the log. Classes started again in late January. But the number of log submissions was still low in February. It was hard to understand why this was. Maybe projects like this start strong and then slow down. We tried to make the project exciting again with Carpool Challenge Week in March. This was a special promotion. It worked and more people filled out the log in March.

It is hard to get people to change their habits. Many people like to drive their cars because it is free to do what they want, when they want. This is a big problem for projects like ours. We need to give people good reasons to change their behavior. We gave prizes to people who participated. The prizes were gift cards to local restaurants, coffee shops, and bookstores. It would be interesting to know if bigger prizes would have worked better. For example, giving away a bicycle or a car could have helped. We did not change the prizes during the project. If we had given better prizes over time, that might have helped. The prizes we gave were good at first. But if we had announced bigger prizes in December and January, people might have been more interested.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security that tracks a group of stocks, a commodity, or a basket of assets. It is more flexible than an index fund and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF gives you the benefits of diversification and single stock ownership. You can sell short, buy on margin, and buy just one share. The cost of an ETF is lower than that of a mutual fund. However, you pay a commission for each trade, like with a stock. There are many ETFs available, each with its own benefits and costs.

We are looking at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of its assets. We want to know if the benefits of owning a single ETF are the same as owning a group of the 10 stocks it holds. We also want to know if there are better ways to own these stocks to get the best results.

To make it easier, we are only looking at the top 10 holdings. Here are the stocks and their percentage of the total assets.

To see how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF, we can use a special calculation to estimate their contributions to a portfolio's risk and return. The chart below shows the calculations.

From the chart, we can see that a portfolio of just the top 10 stocks could give a 6.11% higher return than the ETF. It also has a lower risk, or beta, of 0.12. This means it could be a good option. However, we need to make sure the difference is not just by chance.

To do this, we look at the standard deviation of each stock and compare it to the ETF. Standard deviation is a way to measure risk.

Edgar Allan Poe wrote a famous poem called "Dream-Land." This poem is considered one of his best. In "Dream-Land," Poe used the word "Thulé" in two places. The word "Thulé" comes from Virgil, an old Roman writer. Virgil used it to describe an island north of Britain.

But Poe got the word from another source. He liked the writing of German authors. A man named Karl J. Arndt wrote a book about Poe and another writer. Arndt said Poe copied some of this other writer's work. This other writer was Goethe.

Goethe was a famous writer of Germany. He wrote a play called "Faust." It was published in two parts. The first part came out in 1808, and the second part came out the year Goethe died, 1832. In the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem called "The King of Thulé." This poem is about a king who loses his wife. He starts drinking and crying. He then decides to die.

The king in "The King of Thulé" and the speaker in "Dream-Land" are similar. They both suffer from loss and drink a lot. Goethe's "Faust" was also turned into a romantic play by H.P. Grattan in 1842. This was a year before Poe used the word "Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe used "Thulé" twice in "Dream-Land." He used it at the beginning and end of the poem.

Poe and Goethe are connected through their writing. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a place called Thulé. It is a dark and lonely place. Poe's poem can be read as a companion to Goethe's "The King of Thulé." In Goethe's poem, the king is alone and sad. He has lost his will to rule or live.

Poe admired the work of other writers. He respected Alfred, Lord Tennyson, a British writer. Poe would have known Goethe's work because of his respect for Tennyson. Many copies of Goethe's work were published after the original came out, so Poe would have seen it.

Under California law, can a customer hurt in a fall on applesauce in a grocery store get extra money as punishment? This is because the store manager, Martin, was told twice about the spill and did nothing for 30 minutes to clean it up. He was eating dinner.

A judge will not quickly reject Jennifer Palmer’s claim for extra money as punishment. To get this extra money, Palmer must show that Martin on purpose did something wrong that he knew would hurt someone. She must also show that his actions were very bad. Palmer can say that Martin should have known the danger of not cleaning the spill because many people slipped and fell in the store in the months before her accident. Martin knew this, but he still did nothing.

Palmer can also say that Martin’s actions were very bad because six people slipped and fell in 2009 and he did not take action to keep the store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee, Rich Wayne, told Martin about the applesauce spill. Martin said he was busy eating dinner and did not have time to deal with customer complaints. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Martin about the spill. Martin said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill and hurt her back. Before Palmer fell, five other people had slipped and fallen at D&D Markets in 2009. Palmer is suing D&D for money to pay for her injury and for extra money as punishment.

In California, a person can get extra money as punishment if the other person acted with “badness, cheating, or evil.” The law says that evil means doing something to hurt someone on purpose or doing something very bad without trying to hurt someone. Courts have said that behavior is evil when someone knows that their actions will hurt someone and they do it anyway.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at a college in Canada.  One big question in class was if Islam is a hostile religion.  I think this is a more important question now than ever.  Looking back at what happened since 9/11, I have seen how the media talked about Islam and extremists.  I don't think it was possible in 2001 for an American president with a Muslim background, like Barack Obama, to be elected.

The story of the Prophet Muhammad interests me.  I learned that his history is different from how I thought it was.  I used to think Muhammad forced people to become Muslims.  But his story says he was a victim.  He was humble and kind.  People came to him because they believed in his ideas.

There are some similarities between the teachings of Jesus and what Muhammad did.  One example is when he shared food with many people and there was enough for everyone.  I think the writers of his story wanted to show that Muhammad was a kind and honest person.  But this makes me think they are taking away from Jesus' teachings and trying to make Muhammad seem special.

I also don't like that many stories in the biography are from people who heard from others.  This makes the stories seem less real.  I think it's not good to use stories that are not direct.

What bothers me most is that the story tries to make Muhammad seem like a great and kind person.  But history shows that he did not act that way.  I wonder if Muslims know the real story about Muhammad's rise to power.

This text is about the history of Christianity. After Jesus lived, the ideas he believed in were not followed. Instead, people moved forward with new ideas. If we look at history, we see that Christianity moved away from its start. Now, today, more people are thinking about the past and wanting to go back to the original ideas. They want to know what Jesus really said and meant.

In the future, people will become more interested in the past. They will want to know what was true about Jesus and what was not. This will take a long time, but it will happen. People will try to go back to the ideas Jesus had when he was alive. This will make Christianity return to its original form. A movement will grow and people will try to remove the new ideas that were added. They will go back to what Jesus said, not what others said later.

As this happens, the church will still be strong, but the new ideas will disappear. There will be less difference between different groups of people who believe in Christianity. They will become more alike. This is not the first time this has happened. Remember when Christians were treated badly by the Roman Empire? Later, the Roman Empire became Christian. Our country used to treat African-Americans unfairly, but now they have leaders. The Christian religion will go through a big change. This change will take people back to the beginning.

A way to make this happen is to look at Jesus' words as examples, not as things that must be true. So, what happened after Jesus lived?

We can look far back in history and see that there was only one religion, Judaism. This was the start of Christianity. People believed in one God and the Jewish scriptures were important. When the Romans took control of Jerusalem, the Jewish people were not all alike. They were divided into groups like the Sadducees, Pharisees, and others.

I think the book The Jungle shows that people are often selfish and only look out for themselves. They want to make their lives better, but they do not care about others. The book shows this in many ways. 

One main way is the factory owners and managers. They want to make their factories big and powerful. They do not care about people or animals who might be hurt by their actions. The book says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky." This shows the big damage that factories are doing. The owners do not care about the pollution from the factories or the dirty water from the animal pens. 

The owners and managers also did not care about their workers. The workers were very poor and worked in bad conditions. The factory owners would do anything to make more money. The book says, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a cauldron of hatreds and jealousies." This means the owners and workers did not care about each other. The workers were forced to work very long hours, and then the owners would lay them off without giving them any money or help finding a new job. 

In the past, there were no laws to protect workers. This meant the factory owners and managers could do what they wanted. The workers lived in very bad conditions and were treated like slaves. The book says, "Here is a population on the verge of starvation. They depend on the factory owners for their lives, and the owners are just as cruel as old-time slave drivers." This means the workers were treated very badly and had no way out of their situation.

Many authors use special ways to make readers feel a certain way about important things. Some methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these methods in his book The Great Gatsby. He pairs words that do not usually fit together to create a certain feeling. He also gives meaning to a symbol, then uses it to create a certain feeling.

Fitzgerald uses colors in a special way. He gives a special meaning to white and gray, and uses them to show the reader a certain feeling. In The Great Gatsby, he builds up the meaning for white and gray. White is like a nice, important color, and gray is like an old, faded color.

Fitzgerald shows this meaning at the beginning of the book. He says people are always wearing white. For example, Daisy and Jordan are always dressed in white. Even Nick wears white clothes to Gatsby's party. But then Fitzgerald shows people who are not wearing white. He uses these colors to show that some people are more important and some are not.

Fitzgerald also uses these colors for common things. He says Nick goes down "white chasms" when he goes to work. He says the names of people at Gatsby's parties are "gray names". He uses these colors to show that some things are important and some are not.

Later, Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show that some people are not important. He says Daisy is dressed in white, and people start to think of her as just a person that Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses this method to make readers feel a certain way about Daisy.

San Diego County is a good place for growing food. The climate is mild and sunny. Many types of food grow well here, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers.

There is a strong demand for organic food in San Diego. Many people want to buy food from local farms that use natural methods. Some farms offer tours and let visitors walk on the land. This type of farm can get government help and also make money from tours and educational programs.

Organic farming is good for the environment. It helps keep the soil and water clean. This can lead to more wildlife in the area. But organic farming can be more expensive than other types of farming. It takes more work to remove weeds and pests, and to fertilize the soil without using chemicals. Organic farms are often smaller than big farms, so they do not have the same efficiency.

The chosen land is a 160-acre area next to the town of Potrero in San Diego County, California. The land has chaparral, grass, and oak trees, and is near the Cleveland National Forest. This area is home to many types of plants and animals. Some of these animals are in danger, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher.

People have lived on this land for a long time. First, it was Native Americans, then cattle ranchers and wood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of a original homestead patent, so it was probably used for grazing or wood production for many years.

I looked at a real estate website to find a property, and then I researched government programs that can help small farmers. I found an organic farm in the same area that is an example of what this land might become.

Culture is very important in any negotiation. What culture is and what it means can be tricky to understand. A culture is not the same everywhere or for everyone. People often think of a culture as a specific thing. But it is not. For example, saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are polite" is not true. Every person is different. 

To understand a culture, you must learn about its history, its attitudes and its values. You must not judge a culture as good or bad. You must accept it for what it is. This is especially important when you are dealing with a culture that is very different from your own.

If you are in a foreign country, you must respect its traditions and customs. You must be honest and show respect. If you are in a place where the culture is very different from your own, you must be extra careful. You can learn a lot about a culture by studying its history, its values and its customs. 

A company also has its own culture. This is true even in the same country. Every company is different. For example, some companies encourage people to work long hours while others give them more time off. You can see the culture of a company by looking at how its employees dress, how they communicate with each other and how they hire new people. 

Values are very important to understand. They tell you why people behave in certain ways. If people in a culture value harmony, they will not want to cause trouble. If people in a culture value winning, they will want to win at all costs. Understanding these values will help you in a negotiation. You must also try to learn about the person you are negotiating with. This will help you to make a good deal.

The Bible says, "The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This idea is found in the Christian Bible and is also a point made by Thomas Aquinas. Both writers are trying to say God exists. We can compare their ideas because they both think of God as the God of the Bible.

Let's look at St. Anselm's idea first. He says that God is like a truth inside our minds. We know God exists because we know God is true. Anselm thinks we don't need proof from outside to know God. This is called faith. We trust in God without needing proof.

Now, let's look at St. Thomas Aquinas. He says we can know God exists through reason. We can see proof that God is real. Aquinas uses five different ideas to help us understand God. These ideas are change, causation, contingency, excellence, and harmony. He thinks that if we know the parts of something, we can know the whole. He says we can know God just by looking at the world around us.

These two writers have different ideas about how to know God. Anselm thinks faith is enough, but Aquinas thinks reason is better. We will discuss this further.

A long time ago, over two thousand five hundred years, a prince was born. He would one day be called Buddha. He grew up and later rejected the world. He became very wise and his teachings formed the new religion of Buddhism. But Buddhism has changed over time. This is clear in the country of Sri Lanka, where people celebrate the annual water-cutting ceremony. This ceremony is very important, but it was not taught by Buddha. It shows that Buddhism is different today than it was when Buddha was alive. This is true for many things, from small traditions to the main ideas of the religion.

This change is caused by many things, both from inside and outside Buddhism. Inside Buddhism, some people's ideas have changed over time. Outside Buddhism, other people's ideas have also made Buddhism different. Sometimes these changes are small and sometimes they are big.

We will use some special words in this discussion. Internal means a force that comes from people who believe in Buddhism. External means a force from people who do not believe in Buddhism. A hostile force is one that hurts or wants to hurt Buddhism. A benign force is one that does not want to hurt or help Buddhism.

First, we will look at the main ideas of Buddhism. These ideas are very important. Buddhists look to three things for help: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the teachings, which include many texts. These texts are divided into three parts: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has all the teachings of the Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for Buddhist monks and nuns. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the universe. These ideas include the idea of no soul, suffering in life, and that everything is changing.

If people understand these ideas, they can stop suffering. Suffering is a cycle of life and death. This cycle is called Sansara. When people are enlightened, they will no longer suffer from desire, hatred, and delusion. Buddhists also follow rules to live a good life. Laypeople follow five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not have sex with someone you should not, and do not take too much drink. Monks and nuns follow many more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico are two countries with a long history of rivalry. This rivalry lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The biggest problem between the two countries was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. In this war, the United States defeated Mexico and took control of Texas and the American Southwest. Many other problems happened between the two countries. These problems ended just before World War I. The rivalry started because Americans and Mexicans did not agree on many things, such as religion, customs, and traditions. They also had different interests. 

This is like many other countries that have a long rivalry with a neighbor. Countries that share a border often have disagreements that lead to a rivalry. The United States and Mexico are like many other countries with a long history of rivalry. David M. Pletcher (1977) says, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). These two countries are close to the United States and have been rivals for a long time. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States. 

The two countries disagreed on religious issues. This is a problem that has happened many times in history. Sally Frahm (2001) says, “In the past, Americans were opposed to Catholicism” (p. 86). Like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union, the rivalry between the United States and Mexico was partly about ideas and partly about what each country wanted. In this case, the ideas were about religion. The two countries did not trust each other because of the distrust between the English and Spanish. This distrust was a big problem in the early days of their relationship. 

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 problems between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these problems were about territory. The United States and Mexico had many disagreements about border raids and other problems along the border. These problems did not end until both countries used their armies to control their borders. (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). 

Schmitt (1974) says the rivalry between the two countries started to end when Mexico became dependent on the United States. The rivalry ended when the United States stopped trying to take more land from Mexico and instead wanted to help Mexico in other ways.

Fifteen years ago, I got very sick suddenly. I was a nurse at that time. I chose nursing because my childhood was not safe. People said, "You'll always get a job because people will always be sick." I wanted a safe job. My dream was to be a scientist or a journalist. But I chose nursing instead.

Now I am 46 years old and single. I have no money and I cannot work. To this day, I am still sick. I get money from the government because I am too sick to work. After 15 years, I have nothing. Every day is hard. I am not safe, I am not secure, and I do not like how I feel about myself.

But I know one thing is true. I would not have made it without my family and friends helping me. I was very weak when I got sick. When disaster strikes, people do not feel strong.

My point is that bad things will always happen. We cannot guarantee that everything will be okay. No matter how well we prepare, some things are too big for one person to handle.

I agree that we should not trust the government too much. But I think we should help each other instead of relying on the government. We should learn to ask for help and to help others.

The people who built this country did not do it alone. They helped each other. They shared what they had. The people who crossed the country in wagons did not do it alone. They worked together.

By all means, be prepared. I have a disaster kit and first aid supplies. But I also know my neighbors. That is the most important thing. Get to know the people who live near you. They can be your friends in hard times.

We want to know why living things change over time. Are there limits that stop this change from happening? Scientists still do not fully understand this. In nineteen seventeen, a scientist named D'Arcy Thompson said it is hard to describe the shapes of living things using math. However, scientists are now using math to study how shells grow in certain animals.

We are studying how the shells of a certain type of animal called Prunum change over time. We are using math and experiments to understand how these changes happen. We looked at pictures of Prunum shells and used math to create models of how the shells might look. We then compared these models to real shells.

A shell is a tube that grows over time. It turns in a circle, or spiral, as it grows. This spiral is made up of many round circles, called whorls. Whorls are connected by a line called a suture. The last whorl, or body whorl, is the largest. The tip of the spiral is called the apex, and the bottom is called the base.

We can look at shells from different angles. There are four main ways to look at a shell: from the top, from the bottom, from the side, and from the front. The most common way to look at a shell is from the side, with the front facing the viewer.

To count the whorls on a shell, we look at it from the top and find the first line that divides the shell. We then count the whorls from this line, counting a quarter of a whorl if it is not a whole one.

A shell can be thought of as a path that the animal walks through time and space as it grows its shell. We can follow this path by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the whorl. We can use math to represent this path. Once we have this math, we can change the way the shell grows.

Indonesia has problems with many babies dying before they are one year old and after they are born.  This has not gotten better in the last ten years.  Indonesia is working to meet its goals made in 2000.  But the country is not improving as fast as it should in the important areas of child and mother health.

One good thing is that now 72% of babies have a trained health worker helping them when they are born.  But this number still has problems.  Some of these workers are not doctors and cannot help if a problem happens during birth.  This means many women die during birth.  Indonesia is not doing enough in this area.

Another problem is that fewer children under five who get sick with diarrhea are getting help from a health worker.  We also do not have enough information about how well mothers are taking care of themselves after giving birth.

Few mothers in Indonesia have a surgery called a cesarean section.  This is not good.  Even in cities, only 7% of mothers have this surgery.  In small towns, it is only 2%.  This means that many women in small towns do not have easy access to healthcare.

Some people do not have healthcare services because they are too poor.  They cannot afford to pay for the help they need.  This is a big problem.

So, the big question is: how can Indonesia fix these problems?  Should the country make special programs to help one area at a time, or should it make the healthcare system better overall?  Making special programs can be good because they have clear goals and can make things happen quickly.  But making the healthcare system better can help more people and is more important in the long run.

The problem with making special programs is that they can take money and workers away from other areas of healthcare.  This can cause other problems, like making it harder for people to get the help they need.

Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights are two novels that do not follow the normal way of Victorian novels.  Victorian novels are known for being very detailed about the lives of the wealthy people of that time.

But these two novels are different. They have mystery and strange events that make the characters more interesting. This makes us understand their feelings and reasons for doing things.

In the middle of the night, Oliver heard many confusing and scary ideas in his head. It was as if he was still talking to two men who were angry with each other. He was unsure of his body and his mind. He heard the sound of guns and people shouting. He saw lights and felt a lot of noise. He was moved quickly away from the noise. He felt pain all the time.

In Oliver Twist, strange events like this help us understand Oliver's feelings. These events show what hurts Oliver and what he thinks about the world around him. Later in the book, Oliver remembers the time he was shot. He remembers it like a dream. He is still in pain and does not know what to do. The pain makes him feel scared. It makes him think that he cannot control his life.

Oliver feels sad and helpless. He does not try to control what happens to him. This shows that Oliver does not have much control over his life. He is easily hurt by the people around him. He is hurt by Fagin, the old man who owns him.

In Wuthering Heights, there is also a strange and scary time. The day was short and night was long. It was not a normal day. The night was quiet but felt very long. Some people thought that time was passing slowly.

I worked with a group that helped students after school. I helped them with their studies. I worked with a boy named Adrian. He was having trouble reading. I thought something was strange. Some words he could read easily, but others he could not. He spoke good English, but I was sure he was of Latino descent. I met his mother one day. She did not speak English. She only spoke Spanish. We used a few words in Spanish to talk. I then understood the problem. Adrian was good at reading, but he did not know the alphabet. I tried to help him. I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story for two reasons. First, it shows that language can be a big problem in schools. Second, it shows that the problem is not always easy to see. Even if a child speaks good English, reading can still be hard. We all know that this is a problem. So, what do we do? In Adrian's case, I helped him with reading. But for other children who do not speak much English, the problem is more complicated. There is no one answer. We need to use many different ways to help.

One good idea is the dual language system. This means teaching children in two languages. Not just for children who speak Spanish at home, but for all children. This system works well. Children in dual language classes do better in school. Some people are afraid of this idea. They think it is not worth the money. But it is true. All children would benefit from this system if we used it more. To make it work, we do not need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have helpers who are bilingual. This can make a big difference.

Most of us are told from a young age that there is something bigger than us. Some people go to Sunday school, others to the Temple, and some search for answers on their own. Many of us believe what our parents teach us. But some of us disagree and think there is no more to life than what we can see and touch. We may change our values many times. Each person's idea of spirituality is different.

My father said cardinals are his favorite birds. We sat on our front porch and listened to the rain. Rain poured down from the gutters and drowned the plants. My father looked out at the rain, thinking or remembering something. He was thinner and looked tired. His hair was thinning too. I was afraid and sad because my father was going to die. I didn't want to talk about it because it would make it more real. I hugged him and sat close to him.

My father died in December, five days after my birthday. He was in pain, but treatment kept him alive a few more months. I didn't understand why he had to suffer so long. I thought to myself, what kind of God would do this? I didn't say any prayers that night. If God existed, I thought, he wasn't listening to me.

I didn't want to watch my father die. I chose to remember him the way he lived, not how he died. My father would have wanted me to be happy, not sad. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for the news. But no one called me.

The term "Gothic Novel" is a combination of old and new ideas. Ian Watt describes it as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New.'" Many people have different opinions about Gothic novels. Some think they are not very deep, while others think they are great. The first Gothic novel was written by Horace Walpole in 1764. It is called "The Castle of Otranto." Walpole used old ideas and new ways of writing to create a new kind of story.

Walpole's "Gothic Story" combines old and new elements. He used old theatrical ideas and new ways of writing to create a new kind of story. The Gothic genre also uses old ideas about medieval times, such as gothic architecture and traditions.

When "The Castle of Otranto" was first published, the word "gothic" was used to describe many different things. Some people thought it was old-fashioned and not very sophisticated. The combination of old and new ideas makes Gothic novels remain popular for a long time.

One idea that is important in Gothic novels is the concept of chivalry. Chivalry is a medieval idea about how to be a good knight.
